<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  macOS entitlements for Guy Code.

  Why this file exists, even though we ship ad-hoc-signed without
  notarization:
    1. Apple Silicon refuses to launch unsigned arm64 binaries. We
       satisfy that with electron-builder's `identity: "-"` (ad-hoc
       signature via codesign -s -). Ad-hoc signing requires
       SOMETHING to sign, and electron-builder applies the
       entitlements named here during that step. Without an
       entitlements file, the ad-hoc sign still works but Chromium
       can be denied capabilities at runtime that we want it to
       have (JIT for V8, dyld variables for the renderer, etc.).
    2. When we eventually buy an Apple Developer cert and turn on
       `hardenedRuntime: true` + notarization, THIS file is what
       Apple's notary service inspects. Shipping it now means the
       eventual signing/notarization PR is purely a secrets +
       config change — no entitlements scramble at the finish line.

  What's enabled and why:
    com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit                  — V8 JIT
    com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory
                                                     — Node's V8
                                                       requires
                                                       writable+
                                                       executable
                                                       memory pages
    com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables
                                                     — Electron's
                                                       launcher
                                                       sets DYLD_*
                                                       for the
                                                       helper procs
    com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation
                                                     — Allows
                                                       loading
                                                       Chromium
                                                       helper
                                                       frameworks
                                                       signed with
                                                       a different
                                                       team ID
                                                       (electron's)
                                                       than ours.
                                                       Standard
                                                       requirement
                                                       for any
                                                       Electron
                                                       app.

  What's NOT enabled and why:
    No network/files/microphone/camera/etc. entitlements — under
    hardenedRuntime+sandbox those would matter, but we're not
    sandboxed (we're a developer tool that needs to drive the user's
    filesystem and arbitrary subprocesses; sandboxing would be
    crippling). Leaving these out keeps the entitlement set minimal
    and reviewable.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-dyld-environment-variables</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
